          3rd Topic: Advanced operators
        </h1>
        <p>
          Advanced operators not usually used in elementary but will come in handy for future lessons. The 2 that will be discussed is exponents and roots. <br>
          Exponents are basically just repeated multiplication. It is denoted as a^b where a is the base and b is the exponent. To evaluate this, you have to multiply a by itself b times <br>
          For example, 3^4 can be rewritten as 3*3*3*3 which is 81. Notice that 3 (base) was multiplied to itself 4 times (exponent) <br>
          Next that we're going to discusse are roots. Its general formula is a√(b). It is just like asking "what is a number that when I exponentiate a will result in b?" <br>
          An example would be 3√(27). We are tasked to find the number that when exponentiated by 3, will result in 27. For this expression, the answer is 3 because 3^3 will be 27.
        </p>
